-- =============================================================================
-- Section 12: Markov's Principle from Stone Duality
-- =============================================================================

-- The library provides a proof that Markov's principle follows from Stone Duality.
-- Here we show how to use it and state additional consequences.

-- Markov's principle: if a sequence is not all zeros, we can find a one.
-- This is proved in OmnisciencePrinciples.Markov from Stone Duality via
-- the observation that if ╬▒ РЅб 0, then Sp(2/╬▒) is inhabited.

-- Assuming Stone Duality, we can derive MP:
-- From Stone Duality: evaluation map B Рєњ 2^(Sp B) is an equivalence for B : Boole¤Ѕ
-- Given ╬▒ : 2^РёЋ with ┬г(Рѕђn. ╬▒n = 0), consider the quotient 2/╬▒.
-- If Sp(2/╬▒) were inhabited, we'd have a map 2/╬▒ Рєњ 2,
-- but this would make ╬▒ identically 0, contradiction.
-- So Sp(2/╬▒) is empty, meaning 0 = 1 in 2/╬▒, meaning some ╬▒n = 1.

-- =============================================================================
-- Section 13: LLPO from Stone Duality
-- =============================================================================

-- The proof of LLPO from Stone Duality (see main-monolithic.tex) goes as follows:
--
-- 1. B_Рѕъ is the Boolean algebra generated by (g_n)_{n:РёЋ} with relations g_m РѕД g_n = 0 for m РЅа n.
--    Its spectrum РёЋРѕъ = Sp(B_Рѕъ) consists of sequences hitting 1 at most once.
--
-- 2. Define f : B_Рѕъ Рєњ B_Рѕъ ├Ќ B_Рѕъ by:
--    f(g_n) = (g_k, 0) if n = 2k
--    f(g_n) = (0, g_k) if n = 2k+1
--
-- 3. This map is injective (well-defined by the relations).
--
-- 4. By Stone Duality axiom "surjections are formal surjections":
--    f injective РЪ╣ Sp(f) : Sp(B_Рѕъ ├Ќ B_Рѕъ) Рєњ Sp(B_Рѕъ) is surjective.
--
-- 5. Since Sp(B_Рѕъ ├Ќ B_Рѕъ) РЅЁ РёЋРѕъ + РёЋРѕъ, we get a surjection s : РёЋРѕъ + РёЋРѕъ Рєњ РёЋРѕъ.
--
-- 6. For any ╬▒ : РёЋРѕъ, there exists x : РёЋРѕъ + РёЋРѕъ with s(x) = ╬▒.
--    - If x = inl(╬▓), then ╬▒_{2k+1} = 0 for all k.
--    - If x = inr(╬▓), then ╬▒_{2k} = 0 for all k.

-- We postulate LLPO as an axiom that follows from Stone Duality.
-- The full proof requires setting up B_Рѕъ quotients which is done in the library.

postulate
  llpo : LLPO

-- =============================================================================
-- Section 14: Consequences of LLPO
-- =============================================================================

-- LLPO implies that closed propositions are closed under finite disjunctions.
-- This is because LLPO is equivalent to the statement:
-- (┬гP Рѕе ┬гQ) Рєћ ┬г(P РѕД Q) for open P, Q

-- Given P, Q closed propositions:
-- P Рєћ Рѕђn. ╬▒n = 0, Q Рєћ Рѕђn. ╬▓n = 0
-- We want: P Рѕе Q is closed.
--
-- P Рѕе Q Рєћ (Рѕђn. ╬▒n = 0) Рѕе (Рѕђn. ╬▓n = 0)
--
-- Define ╬│ : РёЋРѕъ by: ╬│(2k) = ╬▒(k), ╬│(2k+1) = ╬▓(k)
-- (But ╬│ may hit 1 more than once if both ╬▒ and ╬▓ hit 1.)
--
-- Instead, we use LLPO on sequences that hit at most once.

-- For the full characterization, we would prove:
-- LLPO Рєћ "For open P, Q: (┬гP Рѕе ┬гQ) Рєћ ┬г(P РѕД Q)"
--
-- This is Proposition 1.4.1 of Diener's book on constructive reverse mathematics.

-- Closed propositions closed under disjunction (using LLPO)
-- The direct proof is more involved; we sketch the idea:

-- Given ╬▒, ╬▓ : 2^РёЋ witnessing closedness of P, Q:
-- P Рєћ Рѕђn. ╬▒n = 0, Q Рєћ Рѕђn. ╬▓n = 0
--
-- To show P Рѕе Q is closed, we need ╬│ : 2^РёЋ with:
-- (P Рѕе Q) Рєћ Рѕђn. ╬│n = 0
--
-- The issue is P Рѕе Q = (Рѕђn. ╬▒n = 0) Рѕе (Рѕђn. ╬▓n = 0), which is NOT the same as
-- Рѕђn. (╬▒n = 0 Рѕе ╬▓n = 0) (the latter is weaker).
--
-- LLPO bridges this gap for suitable sequences.

-- For now, we postulate closedOr as following from LLPO:
postulate
  closedOr : (P Q : hProp РёЊ-zero) Рєњ isClosedProp P Рєњ isClosedProp Q
           Рєњ isClosedProp (РѕЦ РЪе P РЪЕ Ріј РЪе Q РЪЕ РѕЦРѓЂ , squashРѓЂ)

